## 9. Dashboard

### Tech Stack

- **Framework**: Next.js (TypeScript)
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS
- **State management**: React hooks + SWR for data fetching
- **Real-time**: WebSocket for build log streaming
- **Deployed**: Dogfooded on the platform itself

### Pages

#### 1. Projects List (`/`)
- Grid/list of all connected repos
- Each card shows: project name, repo link, latest deployment status, production URL
- "Connect Repo" button (triggers GitHub App installation flow)

#### 2. Project Detail (`/projects/:id`)
- Current production URL (clickable)
- Recent deployments (list with status, commit, branch, duration, timestamp)
- Quick actions: Deploy, Rollback, View Logs
- Tabs: Deployments | Settings | Environment | Database

#### 3. Deployment Detail (`/projects/:id/deployments/:deploymentId`)
- Build logs (streamed in real-time during build, stored after completion)
- ANSI color support for build output
- Deployment metadata: commit SHA, branch, duration, image size
- Preview URL (if preview deployment)
- Rollback button ("Deploy this version to production")

#### 4. Project Settings (`/projects/:id/settings`)
- Build settings: build command, output directory, framework override
- Production branch selection
- deploy.yaml preview (read-only, shows detected config)
- Danger zone: disconnect repo, delete project

#### 5. Environment Variables (`/projects/:id/environment`)
- Toggle between Production and Preview scopes
- Key-value editor (add, edit, delete)
- Secret toggle per variable
- Bulk edit (paste multiple KEY=VALUE lines)

#### 6. Database (`/projects/:id/database`)
- Connection string (show/hide password)
- Database stats (size, active connections)
- "Create Database" if none exists
- "Delete Database" with confirmation

#### 7. Rollback (`/projects/:id/deployments`)
- Deployment history with "Rollback to this version" button per entry
- Shows which deployment is currently active (production)
- Rollback confirmation dialog

#### 8. Settings (`/settings`)
- GitHub App connection status
- Notification preferences (Slack/Discord webhook URL)
- Platform info (VPS status, disk usage, container count)

### Auth Flow

1. User visits platform dashboard
2. Redirected to GitHub OAuth (via GitHub App)
3. After authorization, GitHub returns auth code
4. Platform exchanges code for user token
5. Platform verifies user is the allowed GitHub user (hardcoded user ID or GitHub username)
6. Issues JWT session token, stored in HTTP-only cookie
7. All API requests include the session cookie

